üß© If This ‚Üí Then That (Decision Tree)
Situation	Next Move
BloodHound shows CanRDP	Try RDP to host with xfreerdp or mstsc
BloodHound shows CanPSRemote	Use evil-winrm or Enter-PSSession
BloodHound shows SQLAdmin	Use PowerUpSQL or mssqlclient.py, check for SeImpersonatePrivilege
User can't RDP but is in Remote Desktop Users group	Validate RDP access manually
User can't PSRemote but is in Remote Management Users	Try WinRM anyway
Found SQL creds in web.config/snaffler	Use mssqlclient.py or PowerUpSQL to enumerate
SeImpersonatePrivilege present	Use JuicyPotato/PrintSpoofer to escalate to SYSTEM
üîç Key Hints & Things to Look Out For
üß® Domain Users can RDP? Often a jackpot.

üß® Execution without Admin Rights ‚Äì still lethal. Always test.

üß® SQL creds from config files (Snaffler/Web.config) ‚Üí Often lead to SYSTEM-level access.

üß® WinRM Access? Rarely defended well. Easy way in.

üß® Don‚Äôt stop at GUI access ‚Äî once on the host, dump creds, check privileges, find escalation vectors.

üß® On the exam, any remote execution path = huge pivot point. Exploit it, escalate, repeat.

üìå Final CPTS Reminders
üîÅ Enumeration is iterative. After every user/host compromise ‚Üí Re-run BloodHound.

üîë Access ‚â† privilege. A low-priv user with CanPSRemote is more dangerous than you think.

üéØ These paths can get you onto a host where:

You dump more hashes

Steal tokens

Dump LSASS

Get local admin ‚Üí Dump SAM, SYSTEM, SECURITY

Or find DCSync-capable users
